	<div class="intro-section">
		<p class="lead">Your fence color significantly impacts your property's curb appeal, and the right choice can make your home stand out beautifully in your Stockton neighborhood. Whether you're staining a new wood fence, choosing vinyl colors, or planning an iron fence finish, these 2026 color trends will help you make a stylish, timeless choice.</p>
	</div>

	<h2>Top Fence Color Trends for 2026</h2>

	<h3>1. Warm Charcoals and Soft Blacks</h3>
	<p>Dark, sophisticated tones continue dominating fence design. Unlike harsh pure blacks, the trend favors:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Charcoal Gray:</strong> Deep gray with subtle warmth</li>
		<li><strong>Graphite:</strong> Nearly black with blue undertones</li>
		<li><strong>Soft Black:</strong> Less stark than pure black, more forgiving</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Modern and contemporary homes, creating dramatic backyard spaces, iron and aluminum fences.</p>
	<p><strong>Stockton consideration:</strong> Dark colors absorb heat—may not be ideal for areas where pets rest against the fence in summer.</p>

	<h3>2. Natural Cedar and Warm Wood Tones</h3>
	<p>The organic, natural look remains hugely popular. Transparent and semi-transparent stains that showcase wood grain are trending:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Honey Cedar:</strong> Light, golden warmth</li>
		<li><strong>Natural Redwood:</strong> Rich reddish-brown tones</li>
		<li><strong>Driftwood:</strong> Weathered gray-brown natural look</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Traditional homes, natural landscapes, those who appreciate wood's inherent beauty.</p>
	<p><strong>Maintenance note:</strong> Natural tones require more frequent re-staining to maintain appearance.</p>

	<h3>3. Greige (Gray + Beige)</h3>
	<p>This sophisticated neutral bridges cool grays and warm beiges, offering incredible versatility:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Complements virtually any home exterior color</li>
		<li>Works with both warm and cool landscaping</li>
		<li>Hides dirt and weathering better than pure white or gray</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Those wanting a neutral, elegant look that complements rather than competes.</p>

	<h3>4. Deep Forest Greens</h3>
	<p>Green fences are making a comeback, particularly deep, sophisticated tones:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Hunter Green:</strong> Classic and timeless</li>
		<li><strong>Forest Green:</strong> Deep, rich green</li>
		<li><strong>Sage Green:</strong> Softer, more muted option</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Properties with lush landscaping, those wanting fence to blend with gardens, traditional/colonial-style homes.</p>

	<h3>5. White and Off-White</h3>
	<p>Classic white remains popular, especially in updated variations:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Bright White:</strong> Clean, crisp traditional look</li>
		<li><strong>Creamy White:</strong> Warmer, less stark</li>
		<li><strong>Antique White:</strong> Subtle yellow undertone for vintage appeal</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Classic American homes, farmhouse style, creating the illusion of larger spaces.</p>
	<p><strong>Consideration:</strong> Shows dirt and requires more frequent cleaning, especially in Stockton's dusty summers.</p>

